(12, 2, '2018-04-13 00:00:00', '2018-04-13 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 30px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\"><a><img style=\"width: auto; max-width: 100%;\" src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/namesfor10b-screenshot2-enlarged_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Names for 10 Game\" /></a>\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\">Sofia plays the Names for 10 game with her fingers.</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-size: large;\">In the previous <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Names for 10 post</a>, 7-year-old Eli showed you the secret for making math easier for kids (and adults) using a small (delicious) pile of M&amp;Ms.</span></div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: large;\"> 10 + 0,  9 + 1,  8 + 2,  7 + 3,  6 + 4,  5 + 5,\n4 + 6,  3 + 7,  2 + 8,  1 + 9,  0 + 10</span></strong></div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Knowing those number partners, backwards and forwards — <strong>the commutative property (a + b = b + a)</strong> — makes so many other math concepts snap into place.\n\nAddition, subtraction, multiplication, division, trading and regrouping (we used to call it carrying and borrowing), fractions, decimals, percentages, time, and money — all become easier.\n\nIn the video below, Sofia shows you how to <strong>practice these critical number partners using her fingers.</strong>\n\nMost of us have 10 of those, right? No additional materials necessary.\n\nAnd playing Names for 10 is a great way to pass the time while you wait in line or ride in a car — with a big payoff!\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube\" style=\"margin-bottom: 40px; margin-top: 10px;\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-wrapper wsite-youtube-size-auto wsite-youtube-align-center\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-container\"><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/yxggj-iUpSM?wmode=opaque\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Some kids (and their parents) <strong>do better remembering the names for 10 when they can see the numbers along with the groups of items.</strong>\n\nIn the next video, Jude, a second-grader, demonstrates how to play the game with <strong>number cards and pennies.</strong>\n\nEach time he moves an item from one pile to the other, he changes the cards to match the number of objects in each of the groupings that add up to 10.\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube\" style=\"margin-bottom: 20px; margin-top: 10px;\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-wrapper wsite-youtube-size-auto wsite-youtube-align-center\">\n<div class=\"wsite-youtube-container\"><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/Y8aAiVfUIe8?wmode=opaque\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Notice that Jude wrote the numbers from 0 to 10 on colored paper, making sure the number partners were the same color.</strong>\n\nWhite paper is fine if that is what\'s available, but when number partners match in color, that gives kids one more way to cement the names for 10 in their brains.\n\n<strong>I’ve found that the more senses people use to learn things, the better they remember.</strong>\n\nMoving objects as well as number cards, especially color-coordinated ones, makes the groupings more visual. The physical shifting of objects also adds to kids’ familiarity with the number combinations that make 10.\n\nWhether your child is in first grade or fifth, or if YOU could use a math hack to make you better at quick calculations — at the grocery store, at work, or anywhere you’d like a fast answer — instantly knowing the names for 10 will make all the difference!\n\n<strong>If you have a math hack to share, please tell us about it in the comment section below.</strong>\n<strong>\nWe’d love to hear from you.</strong>\n\n<strong>And please share <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Names for 10</a> with your friends!</strong>\n\n</div>\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\n<div style=\"height: 0px; overflow: hidden;\"></div>\n<a class=\"wsite-button wsite-button-small wsite-button-normal\" href=\"/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span class=\"wsite-button-inner\">Check out the previous post: “Names for 10” Game</span></a>\n<div style=\"height: 30px; overflow: hidden;\"></div>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"389591743872304966\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\"></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', 'More “Names for 10” Games to Boost Math Skills', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'more-ways-to-play-the-names-for-10-game-to-help-kids-become-math-wizards-and-you-too', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:48:36', '2018-10-10 19:48:36', '', 0, 'https://thebrainstages.com/2018/04/13/more-ways-to-play-the-names-for-10-game-to-help-kids-become-math-wizards-and-you-too/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(13, 2, '2018-05-18 00:00:00', '2018-05-18 00:00:00', '<div></div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Summer vacation gives kids lots of opportunities for free play, which is great for mental processing and creativity. The break between grade levels is a perfect time for kids to get lots of exercise, take a breather from academics, and beef up imaginative play.\n\n<strong>That’s why summer reading is so great!</strong>\n\nBooks offer lots of springboard material to spark kids\' imaginations. Besides, going on mental adventures is a great way to pass the time during those lulls that happen on summer days or for winding down at the end of the bedtime ritual before lights out.\n\n<strong>The best part is children who read fun stories and play some of the Brain Stages games won\'t have to struggle to relearn stuff they\'ve forgotten over the break. In fact, their skills will be even sharper for the coming year.</strong>\n\nThe old saying \"practice makes perfect\" may be an overstatement, but most of us have found that we get better at things when we do them often. The scientific reason is repetition refines neural pathways in the brain and makes them more efficient. Conversely, neglecting those connections makes them rusty, and kids can get frustrated trying to get back into the swing of learning when school starts again.\n\nVisit the local library, book store, or both to find loads of fun for your kids (and you).\nIf your child is happy reading independently, awesome, but don\'t discount the together time in sharing stories, taking turns to read aloud. My kids and I used to check out both kinds of books on every trip to the library — one to read by ourselves and one to share.\n\nMy younger daughter and I read together through her high school years. We loved  discussing the characters, talking about the stories, and predicting what might happen next.\n\nI miss those days. A lot. Take the opportunity to read with your kids while you can.\n\n<strong>The trick is to get books your kids will LOVE, that will take them on adventures, make them laugh and fantasize about other places, sticky situations, and learn about problem solving.</strong>\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 20px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\"><a><img style=\"width: auto; max-width: 100%;\" src=\"https://thebrainstages.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/children-1822474-1920_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages reading list\" /></a>\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Fiction is about problem solving, and kids — well, all of us — can pick up a lot of ideas for real life reading imaginary stories. Authors go to great lengths to research settings, history, and customs to make their stories authentic (I know. I write young adult fiction).\n\nKids can learn as much from a novel, or more, than from a history or science book because they get exposed to concepts within the context of a story.\n\n<strong>For the next several weeks, I\'m going to post lists of tried-and-true titles that have a great reputation for enthralling scads of kids.</strong>\n\nSome of these books have been around for a while. Some are fairly new. All are awesome reads.\n\n<strong>Each list will be geared for a certain reading level.</strong>\n\n<strong>\n</strong><strong>Today\'s post is for second grade, give or take. And I listed series because good books are like cookies or chips — if your kids like one by a certain author, they\'ll probably want more.</strong>\n\nIf your children aren\'t up to this level yet, these will be wonderful read-aloud books to share. And if they usually read harder books, these titles can be quick and easy entertainment. After all, summer is a time to read for pleasure.\n\nI’ve included a list for girls and a list for boys since the genders often show different interests at this age. But feel free to expose both lists to your son or daughter. The best books are the ones they choose for themselves, and all of these books are fun.\n\n<strong>Please share these lists with your friends! Let\'s get lots of kids reading!</strong>\n\n<strong>      Eight Favorite Series of Second Grade Girls (and Boys Too)</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Ivy+and+Bean+series+by+Annie+Barrows\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Ivy and Bean series by Annie Barrows</a>—two unlikely girls become friends and engage in hilarious antics together.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Mercy+Watson+to+the+Rescue+series+by+Kate+DiCamillo&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMercy+Watson+to+the+Rescue+series+by+Kate+DiCamillo\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Mercy Watson to the Rescue series by Kate DiCamillo</a>—the Watsons’ pet pig gets into all kinds of ridiculous trouble trying to save the day.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Science+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AScience+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Super Smart Science Series for kids by April Chloe Terrazas</a>—complicated science concepts explained in an intriguing, understandable way for the younger set.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Gooney+Bird+Greene+series+by+Lois+Lowry&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AGooney+Bird+Greene+series+by+Lois+Lowry\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Gooney Bird Greene series by Lois Lowry</a>—second-grade girl tells “true stories” to her classmates that are quite outlandish and fun.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Toys+Go+Out%3A+Being+the+Adventures+of+a+Knowledgeable+Stingray%2C+a+Toughy+Little+Buffalo%2C+and+Someone+Called+Plastic+&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AToys+Go+Out%3A+Being+the+Adventures+of+a+Knowledgeable+Stingray%5Cc+a+Toughy+Little+Buffalo%5Cc+and+Someone+Called+Plastic+\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Toys Go Out: Being the Adventures of a Knowledgeable Stingray, a Toughy Little Buffalo, and Someone Called Plastic</em></a> by Emily Jenkins (trilogy)—little girls’ toys and their zany adventures together.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Junie+B.+Jones+series+by+Barbara+Park&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AJunie+B.+Jones+series+by+Barbara+Park\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Junie B. Jones series by Barbara Park</a>—hilarious, charming character kids love.</li>\n 	<li>Judy Moody series by Megan McDonald—feisty, socially awkward third-grader who usually learns lessons the hard way; great early chapter books with fun illustrations.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Amelia+Bedelia+chapter+book+series+by+Herman+Perish&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AAmelia+Bedelia+chapter+book+series+by+Herman+Perish\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Amelia Bedelia chapter book series by Herman Perish</a> (nephew of Peggy Perish, author of the picture book series)—entertaining stories that misinterpret idioms and homophones.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong>\nEight Favorite Series of Second Grade Boys (and Girls Too)</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Touchdown+for+Tommy+by+Matt+Christopher&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ATouchdown+for+Tommy+by+Matt+Christopher\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Touchdown for Tommy</em> by Matt Christopher</a>—author of many books about sporty kids.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Stink+series+by+Megan+McDonald&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AStink+series+by+Megan+McDonald\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Stink series by Megan McDonald</a>—Judy Moody’s younger brother, a second-grade boy, gets into all kinds of fun predicaments with the best of intentions.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Stink-O-Pedia%3A+Super+Stink-y+Stuff+from+A+to+ZZZZ++Megan+McDonald&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AStink-O-Pedia%3A+Super+Stink-y+Stuff+from+A+to+ZZZZ++Megan+McDonald\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Stink-O-Pedia: Super Stink-y Stuff from A to ZZZZ</em></a>  also by Megan McDonald—a book of gross facts little boys love.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Super+Super+Smart+Science+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ASuper+Super+Smart+Science+Series+by+April+Chloe+Terrazas\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Super Smart Science series for kids by April Chloe Terrazas</a>—complicated science concepts explained in a way kids can understand and feel smart.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Nate+the+Great+series+by+Marjorie+Weinman+Sharmat&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ANate+the+Great+series+by+Marjorie+Weinman+Sharmat\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Nate the Great mystery series by Marjorie Weinman Sharmat</a>—for kids who need practice to get to grade-level reading and like a good whodunit.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Dog+Man+series+by+Dave+Pilkey&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ADog+Man+series+by+Dave+Pilkey\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Dog Man series by Dave Pilkey</a>—his latest silly series that has kids clamoring for more.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Magic+Tree+House+series+by+Mary+Pope+Osborne&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMagic+Tree+House+series+by+Mary+Pope+Osborne\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Magic Tree House series by Mary Pope Osborne</a>—for various reading levels; brings history to life and promotes conversations about historical events.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Magic+School+Bus+series+by+Joanna+Cole&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMagic+School+Bus+series+by+Joanna+Cole\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Magic School Bus series—mostly by Joanna Cole</a>, also various reading levels; entertaining read-along books about science concepts learned through adventure.</li>\n</ol>\n<span style=\"font-size: large;\"><strong>Remember to share this post with your friends. Let\'s get kids reading this summer!</strong></span>\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"802094443335514253\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\"></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', 'Summer Reading to Keep Kids Sharp: Grade 2', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'summer-fun-to-keep-kids-sharp-grade-2', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:50:03', '2018-10-10 19:50:03', '', 0, 'https://thebrainstages.com/2018/05/18/summer-fun-to-keep-kids-sharp-grade-2/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(14, 2, '2018-05-30 00:00:00', '2018-05-30 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top:0px;padding-bottom:30px;margin-left:0px;margin-right:0px;text-align:center\">\n<a><img src=\"https://thebrainstages.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/children-studying-670663-1920_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Reading List\" style=\"width:auto;max-width:100%\"></a>\n<div style=\"display:block;font-size:90%\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;\">\n<strong>Not only is low-stress reading during the summer a relaxing, healthy pastime that keeps skills sharp, but fun books can make a big difference in helping your child handle social situations.</strong>\n\nUsually, somewhere in third through fifth grade, children begin to recognize the need to navigate relationships. They wade through social dynamics with friends as well as other kids or adults they don’t get along with so well.\n\nBoth fiction and nonfiction stories present conflicts that eventually get solved. Kids can learn a lot about the ins and outs of how to deal with other people from characters in books. In other words:\n\n<strong>Watching how a problem gets worked out in a story is a safe way to process what to do in real-life circumstances</strong>.\n\nIf you read together sometimes, talk to your child about characters’ interactions and ask how they might handle a similar situation. Discussing harmless hypotheticals now could be a huge help in a future emotional scuffle.\n<strong>&nbsp;</strong>\n\n<font size=\"5\"><strong>Check out the list of 14 well-loved books below.</strong></font>\n\nAlthough the list is geared for fourth grade, younger children, or kids not quite ready&nbsp; to read at this level yet, will enjoy these as read-aloud books. Older kids or more advanced readers will sail through these fun stories, perfect for summer. Most of these titles can be found at your public library. The links go to Amazon pages in case you would like to find out more.\n<ol>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=The+Time+Warp+Trio\" target=\"_blank\">The Time Warp Trio</a>, swashbuckling series (16+ books) by Jon Scieszka—sends readers on a journey through events in history.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Magic+School+Bus&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AMagic+School+Bus\" target=\"_blank\">Magic School Bus</a> series (167+ picture and chapter books) most by Joanne Cole—for kids who like science, cool illustrations, and quirky characters. Animated versions reinforce comprehension—available for purchase or library checkout.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Hank+the+Cowdog+&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AHank+the+Cowdog+\" target=\"_blank\">Hank the Cowdog</a> series by John R. Erickson (68+ books)—a dog that always gets into trouble but saves the day in the end, a beloved ongoing series since 1982.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Charlotte%E2%80%99s+Web+and+Stuart+Little&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ACharlotte%E2%80%99s+Web+and+Stuart+Little\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Charlotte’s Web</em> and <em>Stuart Little</em></a> by E.B. White—long-time, beloved grade four stories.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss_2?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Roald&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ARoald\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Matilda, James and the Giant Peach, George’s Marvelous Machine, The BFG, The Witches,</em></a> and more by Roald Dahl—madcap clever books kids love.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss_2?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Heroes+of+Olympus&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AHeroes+of+Olympus\" target=\"_blank\">Heroes of Olympus</a> series (five books) by Rick Riordan—hugely popular with the action-loving set, leveled late third to early fifth grade for independent reading.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss_2?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=39+Clues&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3A39+Clues\" target=\"_blank\">39 Clues</a> series (eleven books) by various authors, including Rick Riordan—fantastic circumstances and nail-biting adventures kids can’t put down.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_ss_c_1_24?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=bruce+coville+magic+shop+books&amp;sprefix=bruce+coville+magic+shop%2Caps%2C5322&amp;crid=39VWLPOLFFHDI&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3Abruce+coville+magic+shop+books\" target=\"_blank\">Magic Shop</a> series (five books) by Bruce Coville—creepy, riveting stories (<em>The Monster’s Ring; Jeremy Thatcher, Dragon Hatcher; Jennifer Murdley’s Toad,</em> and <em>The Skull of Truth</em> are on fourth-grade reading level<em>; Juliet Dove, Queen of Love</em> is leveled for fifth grade).</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_ss_c_1_24?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Adventures+of+Captain+Underpants&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AAdventures+of+Captain+Underpants\" target=\"_blank\">Adventures of Captain Underpants</a> series (ten books) by Dav Pilkey—kooky stories with an unlikely hero who kids get a kick out of, and most of the series is written on fourth-grade reading level.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/search/ref=sr_1_8_hso_sc_smartcategory_2?rh=n%3A4%2Ck%3ALittle+House+on+the+Prairie&amp;keywords=Little+House+on+the+Prairie&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1527708113&amp;sr=8-8-acs&amp;pf_rd_r=DV71KKTMR1VXJ65T4ESR&amp;pf_rd_t=301&amp;pd_rd_i=4&amp;pd_rd_r=b7499b9b-a315-40bb-bd5b-614ff0af3b5a&amp;pd_rd_w=boy8O&amp;pf_rd_p=3127749740981351126&amp;pf_rd_m=ATVPDKIKX0DER&amp;pd_rd_wg=lma06&amp;pf_rd_i=Little+House+on+the+Prairie&amp;pf_rd_s=desktop-sx-inline\" target=\"_blank\">Little House on the Prairie</a> series (nine books) by Laura Ingalls Wilder—historical fiction with lovable characters children have enjoyed for generations.</li>\n 	<li>\n<em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Miraculous-Journey-Edward-Tulane-ebook/dp/B002NC733U/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1527708535&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=The+Miraculous+Journey+of+Edward+Tulane\" target=\"_blank\">The Miraculous Journey of Edward Tulane</a></em> by Kate DiCamillo—a toy rabbit gets lost and tossed into all kinds of crazy places and new adventures. DiCamillo has written several beloved stories at various reading levels.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Ddigital-text&amp;field-keywords=The+Spiderwick+Chronicles\" target=\"_blank\">The Spiderwick Chronicles</a> (four books) by Tony DiTerlizzi—three siblings discover a field guide in the attic, left by their ancestor, that leads them to a dangerous parallel world.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Ddigital-text&amp;field-keywords=Fudge+Judy+Bloom&amp;rh=n%3A133140011%2Ck%3AFudge+Judy+Bloom\" target=\"_blank\">Fudge</a> series (five books) by Judy Bloom—nine-year-old Peter is frustrated by high-maintenance, hilarious little brother Fudge.</li>\n 	<li>\n<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Wrinkle-Time-Quintet-Books-1-5-ebook/dp/B00E71907M/ref=sr_1_5?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1527709744&amp;sr=1-5&amp;keywords=Wrinkle+in+Time\" target=\"_blank\">Wrinkle in Time</a> series (five books, four leveled fourth grade) by Madeleine L’ Engle—one of the first science-fiction fantasy series for children (1962), still beloved today.</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<em>Note: For more lists of favorite titles categorized by reading level, check out these two websites: <a href=\"https://www.the-best-childrens-books.org/\" target=\"_blank\">The Best Children’s Books</a> and <a href=\"https://www.kidsbookseries.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Kids Book Series</a>.</em>\n\n<strong><font size=\"4\">Please share this post with friends and family. Let’s get kids reading this summer!</font></strong>\nIf you or your child have other favorite titles, please tell us about them in a comment below.\n\nAnd we\'d love for you to share reading experiences with your kids. How ’bout an idea for including relaxed reading in a busy family schedule?\n\nBest wishes for a lovely summer!\n\nTrish Wilkinson\n\nCo-author <em>Brain Stages: How to Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It, K – 5 (Available August 28, 2018, <a href=\"https://www.sandrajonaspublishing.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Sandra Jonas Publishing</a>)</em>\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"443533773270165904\" align=\"left\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" class=\"wcustomhtml\">\n<!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\">\n<a class=\"a2a_dd\" href=\"https://www.addtoany.com/share\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_facebook\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_twitter\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_google_plus\"></a> <a class=\"a2a_button_linkedin\"></a></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', 'Summer Reading to Keep Kids Sharp: Grade 4', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'summer-reading-to-keep-kids-sharp-grade-4', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:51:17', '2018-10-10 19:51:17', '', 0, 'https://thebrainstages.com/2018/05/30/summer-reading-to-keep-kids-sharp-grade-4/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(15, 2, '2018-06-21 00:00:00', '2018-06-21 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 30px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\">\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">Woo-hoo!\n\n<strong>November 12, 2018,</strong> <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> will be ready for readers to snap it up and find out lots of insider info and fun, effective ways to nurture kids\' in line with how their brains develop.\n\nYou may have noticed <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> has a new cover too. Double-whoo-hoo!\n\n<a href=\"https://www.sandrajonaspublishing.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Sandra, independent publisher extraordinaire</a>, revised the original cover with the feedback we received from friends and followers. Thanks so much to those of you who provided observations and suggestions!\n\n<a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> is a grade-by-grade book, a <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01DCHZE3A/ref=dp-kindle-redirect?_encoding=UTF8&amp;btkr=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>What to Expect When You’re Expecting</em></a> for elementary school. The idea is to help create a solid academic, social, emotional, and physical foundation to raise happy, well-adjusted children.\n\n<a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/blog/too-much-coincidence-not-to-be-part-of-the-cosmic-plan\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">This project has been in the works for years.</a> But our sources are as up-to-date as you can get. Many cited articles and studies came out <em>this year</em>. I so appreciate Sandra and her crew for allowing me to update things all the way to the deadline to get <em>Brain Stages</em> to the printer for the release of the <a href=\"https://betweenthecoversblog.wordpress.com/2012/01/20/arcs-v-advance-review-copies/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">advance review copies</a> that will be out in mid-July.\n\nNew studies provide ever-greater detail to create an increasingly vivid picture for how children’s brains grow, develop, and learn.\n\nIn turn, I got to add valuable information, games, and activities up to the last second.\n\nSo. Much. Fun.\n\nNot that scientists have brains all figured out. I’m sure lots of new discoveries are on the horizon, and I’ll keep you in-the-know on the Brain Stages blog.\n\n(I’ve developed a sort of obsession with <a href=\"https://www.google.com/alerts\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Google Alerts</a>, to read articles and studies as soon as they’re published.)\n\nAnd Reading <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> will make you feel like you’re talking with a trusted friend, a supportive one with answers backed up by the latest intel and thousands of hours of experience.\n\n<a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em>Brain Stages</em></a> has all kinds of features to save you (or someone you know) time, energy, and anguish to make the child-raising thing a whole lot of fun, such as:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Brain development and function and how to capitalize on meeting children wherever they are in their growth</li>\n 	<li>Social and emotional tendencies at each grade (individuals\' maturity may show up in more than one chapter as no two kids are alike)</li>\n 	<li>Academic expectations in each grade</li>\n 	<li>Ways to keep gifted kids engaged and develop their social skills</li>\n 	<li>How to handle special needs for happier, more successful children</li>\n 	<li>Games that boost mental and physical coordination to enhance creativity, math, language, and thinking abilities — best of all,  <em>they make family life more enjoyable and bring relationships closer</em></li>\n 	<li>Activities to foster communication skills</li>\n 	<li>Leveled book lists</li>\n 	<li>Tips for quick, healthy nutrition</li>\n 	<li>True stories that are sure to make you laugh, cry, or just give you relief to know you\'re not the only one . . .</li>\n</ul>\nI could go on and on. There\'s so much great stuff!\n\nBut don\'t worry, <em><a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Brain Stages</a></em> is broken into grade-level chapters, kindergarten through fifth, and will have an index to look up things that interest you.\n\nMan, I would\'ve LOVED to have had <em><a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/book.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Brain Stages</a></em> to support my child-raising journey in those early school years.\n\nWe’re living in exciting times!\n\nKids, parents, teachers, and caregivers have all been stressed out trying to keep up with societal expectations.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: large;\"><em>But less stress, more fun, and better results are right around the corner.</em></span>\n\nHere’s to happier, healthier kids, families, and schools everywhere!\n\n<strong>Please forward this email to your friends, and share the good news on Facebook and Twitter.</strong> Let’s give people something positive to anticipate and celebrate!\n\nLeave a comment if you have something you want to ask or tell us.\n(Maybe tell us what you think of the new cover?)\n\nBest wishes and happy summer!\n\nTrish Wilkinson, co-author\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"473363422707327319\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\"></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"><br />\n</script> <!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', '“Brain Stages” Release is November 12!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'brain-stages-how-to-raise-smart-confident-kids-and-have-fun-doing-it-k-5-will-be-released-august-28', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:50:59', '2018-10-10 19:50:59', '', 0, 'https://thebrainstages.com/2018/06/21/brain-stages-how-to-raise-smart-confident-kids-and-have-fun-doing-it-k-5-will-be-released-august-28/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(16, 2, '2018-07-06 00:00:00', '2018-07-06 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0; margin-right: 0; text-align: center;\">\n\nSome kids love to pour over every printed word they can get their hands on. One of my daughters used to read cereal boxes and the backs of shampoo bottles. My nephew, however, would rather have gone to the dentist than pick up a book. His activity of choice was to play computer games, and my sister had to be diligent to keep his screen time moderate.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\">\n\nWhat can you do if you have a child who doesn’t like to read? You know his neural pathways are busily forming and connecting. Reading practice is important. So how do you get him interested?\n\nThe two things that have worked best to get kids reading in my experience are:\n<ol>\n 	<li>Make them laugh, and</li>\n 	<li>Intrigue them</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0; margin-right: 0; text-align: center;\"><a> <img style=\"width: 347; max-width: 100%;\" src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/published/boys-286151-640.jpg?1530924994\" alt=\"Picture\" /> </a>\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%;\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\">For example, most four- to seven-year-olds love to giggle at funny friends like <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Frog-Toad-Storybook-Treasury-Complete/dp/0062292587/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530923960&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=frog+and+Toad\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Arnold Lobel’s Frog and Toad </a>or <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/?ie=UTF8&amp;keywords=henry+and+mudge&amp;tag=mh0b-20&amp;index=aps&amp;hvadid=78202830882208&amp;hvqmt=p&amp;hvbmt=bp&amp;hvdev=c&amp;ref=pd_sl_40y6afr91g_p\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Cynthia Rylant’s Henry and Mudge</a>. And these stories will give you the opportunity to talk about friendship and other values.\n\nFor tough nuts to crack when it comes to reading, <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Barbara+Park%E2%80%99s+Junie+B.+Jones+&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ABarbara+Park%E2%80%99s+Junie+B.+Jones+\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Barbara Park’s Junie B. Jones </a>books are a riot. Kids often can’t wait to read the next one—and the next. Fair warning, Junie isn’t a perfect character—which is largely what draws children to her adventures. Junie uses the word “stupid” a lot, she tends to be naughty, and her grammar is silly and improper. Though kids find these things hilarious, some parents find them inappropriate.\n\nPersonally, I appreciate how children distinguish between proper and improper behavior—how they tell me what Junie should have done instead of what she chose to do in the story. I also get a kick out of how they laugh when Junie says things like “thinked” instead of “thought.”\n\nBut if you’re uncomfortable with such a character, choose other books and series from the list below.\n\nFor instance, <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss_2?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=David+Adler+Cam+Jansen+&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3ADavid+Adler+Cam+Jansen+\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">David Adler’s Cam Jansen </a>enthralls kids with how she finds and interprets clues, and solves mysteries in her neighborhood. Before you know it, your child will begin to put together clues with Cam and try to figure out the puzzle before she does.\n\nYou can begin reading the books on the list below aloud together. Then take turns reading paragraphs. As your child gets more confident and competent, you can switch off reading pages. After a while, he’ll probably take off on his own reading some of these books in the list below.\n\n<strong>11</strong> <strong>Series and Stories to Motivate Young Readers</strong>\n<ol>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Frog-Toad-Collection-Read-Book/dp/B015IZL1CC/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530829227&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=frog+and+toad+series+books\">Frog and Toad series</a> by Arnold Lobel (4 books)—each has five simple, funny, sometimes instructive and touching stories about a frog and his friend, a toad.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_ss_c_1_23?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=henry+and+mudge+series&amp;sprefix=Henry+and+Mudge+series+%2Caps%2C267&amp;crid=PDZZCS8QYMQY&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3Ahenry+and+mudge+series\">Henry and Mudge series</a> by Cynthia Rylant (29 books, last count)—stories of Henry, a young boy, and his experiences with his huge dog, Mudge.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=You+Read+to+Me%2C+I%E2%80%99ll+Read+to+You+series++&amp;rh=i%3Aaps%2Ck%3AYou+Read+to+Me%5Cc+I%E2%80%99ll+Read+to+You+series++\">You Read to Me, I’ll Read to You series</a> by Mary Ann Hoberman (5 books)—collections of simple short fairy tales, fables, scary stories, and more.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Daps&amp;field-keywords=Young+Cam+Jansen+series+\">Young Cam Jansen series</a> by David Adler (20 books)—young-reader mysteries solved by a child detective who has a photographic memory.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/gp/bookseries/B00CKCWQ3A/ref=sr_bookseries_null_B00CKCWQ3A\">Tacky the Penguin</a> series by Helen Lester (7 books)—a funny, unique penguin learns to how to live in his community and celebrate his differences.</li>\n 	<li><em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Wish-That-Duck-Beginner-Books/dp/0394800400/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530827623&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=I+wish+I+had+Duck+Feet\">I wish I had Duck Feet</a></em> by Theo. LeSeig (a.k.a. Dr. Seuss), and lots of other Dr. Seuss books. Kids love LeSieg/Seuss’s strange characters and silly rhymes.</li>\n 	<li><em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Emilys-First-100-Days-School/dp/0786813547/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530827541&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=Emily%E2%80%99s+First+100+Days+of+School\">Emily’s First 100 Days of School</a></em> by Rosemary Wells—fun, adventure, math, what’s not to like in Emily’s, the resident bunny’s early school days?</li>\n 	<li><em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Boy-Who-Loved-Words-ebook/dp/B00DACZ9PQ/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1530827454&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=the+boy+who+loved+words\">The Boy Who Loved Words</a></em> by Roni Schotter—a boy plays with words in silly, enjoyable ways that introduce vocabulary and word patterns.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Miss-Smiths-Incredible-Story-Book/dp/0525471332\">Miss Smith’s Incredible Story Book series</a> (4 books) by Michael Garland—teacher has a magic storybook where characters jump out and students go on adventures.</li>\n 	<li><em><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/There-Was-Old-Lady-Swallowed/dp/0670869392/ref=pd_lpo_sbs_14_img_1?_encoding=UTF8&amp;psc=1&amp;refRID=3DK86PFWAP8CMTJK32K7\">There Was an Old Lady Who Swallowed a Fly</a></em> by Ted Arnold—a funny story that builds on itself with a twist that first-graders love, in context that kids can decode.</li>\n 	<li><a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Junie-First-Ever-Ebook-Collection-ebook/dp/B0082XLMQS/ref=cm_cr_arp_d_product_sims?ie=UTF8\">Junie B. Jones series by Barbara Park</a>, 17 madcap books of Junie’s adventures in kindergarten and 11 books about Junie in first grade</li>\n</ol>\nPsst. Third- and fourth-graders like these stories too, especially kids who need a little extra practice to improve their reading skills.\n\n<strong>Please pass along this post and share it on your social media so we can get as many kids reading as possible!</strong>\n\nDo you have other tried-and-true titles that have helped your child get into reading?\nPlease share them in a comment.\n\nHappy reading!\n\n<strong>Trish Wilkinson</strong>\n\n</div>', 'Entice Kids to Read with Giggles and Intrigue, K – 2', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'entice-kids-to-read-with-giggles-and-intrigue-k-2', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:52:20', '2018-10-10 19:52:20', '', 0, 'https://thebrainstages.com/2018/07/06/entice-kids-to-read-with-giggles-and-intrigue-k-2/', 0, 'post', '', 0);
