(17, 2, '2018-08-08 00:00:00', '2018-08-08 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 30px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\">\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\">Do you have or know a child who writes letters backwards sometimes? The most commonly flipped letters are </span><strong style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\"><em>b</em></strong><span style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\"> and </span><strong style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\"><em>d,</em></strong><span style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\"> but kids have been known to form letters every which way.</span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n\nWhen I was little, I often confused the b and d until I learned the trick Eli and I are about to show you in the less than 3-minute video. The <strong>Red Light, Green Light</strong> game, given to me by a resource specialist in San Diego, incorporates the trick my second-grade teacher gave me (more decades ago than I\'d like to admit).\n\n<strong>Playing Red Light, Green Light has helped kids of all ages, even children who have learning disabilities, figure out which way the letters are supposed to go — not just the b and d but the whole alphabet. </strong>\n\nWe take writing skills for granted, <a href=\"http://theconversation.com/explainer-how-the-brain-changes-when-we-learn-to-read-76783\">but several kinds of connections between neurons, synapses, and little organs in the brain are involved in processing language</a>. It isn’t a wonder that kids get mixed up sometimes. Holding the pencil with an extra finger on top or some other impractical position can make writing harder (click <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/blog/the-best-pencil-grip-the-secret-to-easier-writing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">here</a> to see how to fix pencil grip). Add starting letters in wonky places, or writing letters from the bottom-up instead of the top-down, and writing can become an unpleasant chore.\n\nLuckily, with a bit of fun and practice, neural pathways can access revised information stored in brain’s memory centers.\n\nThe<strong> Red Light, Green Light </strong>game retrains kids how to write letters from <strong>top to bottom</strong> and practices movement from <strong>left to right</strong>, which can improve both reading and writing.\n\nWatch Eli play the game with me in the short video. Initially, when we played the game a few weeks ago, he wrote both <strong><em>b</em></strong> and <em><strong>d</strong></em> from bottom to top. Now that he knows how to form the letters from top to bottom, he told me (and Michelle, his mom, confirmed) that writing has gotten much easier for him. And his reading has improved too!\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"wsite-video\">\n<div class=\"wsite-video-wrapper wsite-video-height-480 wsite-video-align-center\" title=\"Video: red_light_green_light_game_700.mp4\">\n<div id=\"wsite-video-container-884805677828382045\" class=\"wsite-video-container\" style=\"margin: 10px 0 10px 0;\"><iframe id=\"video-iframe-884805677828382045\" src=\"about:blank\" frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"> 						</iframe> <script> 							document.getElementById(\"video-iframe-884805677828382045\").style.opacity = 0; 							document.getElementById(\"wsite-video-container-884805677828382045\").style.background = \"none\"; 							var videoIframe884805677828382045Content = \'<!DOC\'+\'TYPE ht\'+\'ml>\' 								+ \'<he\'+\'ad>\' 								+ \'<scr\'+\'ipt type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/2.1.4/jquery.min.js\">\\x3C/script>\' 								+ \'<scr\'+\'ipt type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"//www.weebly.com/weebly/apps/generateVideo.php?source=weebly&output=js&elementid=884805677828382045&user=114011163&ineditor=0&align=center&margintop=10px&marginbottom=10px&downloadable=1&height=480&video=red_light_green_light_game_700.mp4&image=red_light_green_light_game_700.jpg\">\\x3C/script>\' 								+ \'\'+\'ad>\' 								+ \'<bo\'+\'dy style=\"margin:0; padding: 0;border:none;overflow:hidden;\">\' 								+ \'\'+\'dy>\'+\'ml>\'; 							setTimeout(function() { 								var videoIframe884805677828382045Actual =  document.getElementById(\"video-iframe-884805677828382045\").contentDocument; 								videoIframe884805677828382045Actual.open().write(videoIframe884805677828382045Content); 								videoIframe884805677828382045Actual.close(); 							}, 500); 						</script>\n\n<style> 							#wsite-video-container-884805677828382045{ 								background: url(//www.weebly.com/uploads/red_light_green_light_game_700.jpg); 							}  							#video-iframe-884805677828382045{ 								background: url(//cdn2.editmysite.com/images/util/videojs/play-icon.png?1534365523); 							}  							#wsite-video-container-884805677828382045, #video-iframe-884805677828382045{ 								background-repeat: no-repeat; 								background-position:center; 							}  							@media only screen and (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2), 								only screen and (        min-device-pixel-ratio: 2), 								only screen and (                min-resolution: 192dpi), 								only screen and (                min-resolution: 2dppx) { 									#video-iframe-884805677828382045{ 										background: url(//cdn2.editmysite.com/images/util/videojs/@2x/play-icon.png?1534365523); 										background-repeat: no-repeat; 										background-position:center; 										background-size: 70px 70px; 									} 							} 						</style></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Here\'s how to play Red Light-Green Light</strong>:\n\n1. You’ll need a red crayon and a green crayon. Why crayons? Because kids can feel the wax, and the tactile sensation helps to solidify the concept. You’ll also need lined paper. Any kind will do, but in most grocery stores now, they sell tablets with a top line, a middle dotted line, or \"belt line\", and a bottom line. When learning, or relearning, how to form letters, that belt line is helpful.\n\n2. Remind your child that green means “GO” and red means “STOP.” Put a green dot where the letter begins and continue with green dots for the entire letter on the first several tries. Place a red dot to signify where the letter should stop. Watch to make sure your child begins and ends the letter in the right places.\n\n</div>\n<span style=\"display: table; width: auto; position: relative; float: left; max-width: 100%; ;clear: left; margin-top: 0px; *margin-top: 0px;\"><a><img class=\"galleryImageBorder wsite-image\" style=\"border-width: 0; max-width: 100%; margin: 0px 20px 30px 0px;\" src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/editor/img-1869.jpg?1525727356\" alt=\"Brain Stages Writing Hack\" /></a></span>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left; display: block;\"><em>Note: </em>A lowercase <strong><em>b</em> </strong>starts at the top line, goes down to the bottom line, up to the middle, and around to form the “belly.” After your child gets familiar with how to form the letter, give the direction “Down, up, and around,” and have your child say it with you.</div>\n\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; clear: both; visibility: hidden;\" />\n\n<span style=\"display: table; width: auto; position: relative; float: left; max-width: 100%; ;clear: left; margin-top: 0px; *margin-top: 0px;\"><a><img class=\"galleryImageBorder wsite-image\" style=\"border-width: 0; max-width: 100%; margin: 0px 20px 20px 0px;\" src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/editor/img-1872.jpg?1525727322\" alt=\"Brain Stages Writing Hack\" /></a></span>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left; display: block;\">A lowercase <strong><em>d</em> </strong>is formed like an <em><strong>a</strong></em> with a long stick. Like an <em><strong>a</strong></em> begins just below the middle line, goes up to the middle line, and around to form the “derrier” (French for backside — kids get a kick out of that). The <em><strong>d</strong></em> is formed like an <strong><em>a</em></strong>, except the pencil reaches all the way to the top line and back down to the bottom line. Say with your child, “Around, up, and down.\"</div>\n\n<hr style=\"width: 100%; clear: both; visibility: hidden;\" />\n\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">3. When your child feels comfortable with tracing the letters with lots of green dots, make more letters with fewer and fewer dots until no more are needed. Place only a green dot to mark where the letter begins and a red dot where the letter is to end.\n\n<em>Hint: </em>Get a crayon sharpener (pencil sharpeners work too). Making dots with dull crayons makes them bigger than optimal.\n\nIf your child still reverses a letter using green and red “lights,” help create a tactile memory by writing the entire letter with a green crayon<em>.</em> Then gently guide the pencil in his hand to trace the letter 10 times as consistently as possible.\n\nAnd have fun!\n\nBe liberal with the car engine sounds when you start at the green light and the brake sounds when you stop at the red light.\n\nPlay <strong>Red Light, Green Light </strong>for several days in a row and watch your child\'s writing transform!\n\nThe beauty of educational games is they often have wonderful side effects. <strong>Red Light, Green Light</strong> helps in grasping direction of movement. Truly understanding left to right is a huge help in learning to read.\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"736789382366100066\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\">\n\n\n\n</div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"></script>\n<!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', '“Red Light–Green Light”: Make Kids Better Writers', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'red-light-green-light-make-kids-better-readers', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:38:59', '2018-10-10 19:38:59', '', 0, 'https://thebrainstages.com/2018/08/08/red-light-green-light-make-kids-better-readers/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(18, 2, '2018-08-17 00:00:00', '2018-08-17 00:00:00', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none\" style=\"padding-top: 0px; padding-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 0px; text-align: center;\">\n<div style=\"display: block; font-size: 90%; text-align: left;\"><span style=\"text-align: left; font-size: 16px;\">If you think people are either born good at numbers—or they aren’t—you might be excited to know that a little practice with a few simple games can get anyone calculating quickly in their heads.</span></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align: left;\">\n\nMy older sisters and younger brother always loved math, but I never liked numbers much growing up. My siblings, even my cousins, are all accountants and engineers. The rest of my family seemed to like numbers for numbers’ sake.\n\nMe? I always liked the creative stuff—teaching, storytelling, singing, writing novels and articles, and now <em>Brain Stages</em> with Jackie to help people raise smart, happy kids.\n\nWith math, I went through the motions—I did what I was told to solve problems, usually got the right answer, but didn’t understand how I got there.\n\nAnd forget figuring the cost of something at the grocery store in my head, or any other real-life reason for using math. Without paper and pencil or a calculator, I was lost.\n\nThen I started teaching kids — and I wanted them to understand math better than I did. A fellow teacher showed me the <a href=\"/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\">Names for 10 game</a>, and I learned the same number patterns repeated over and over.\n\n<strong>I learned to apply patterns to larger numbers as well as decimals—in my head!</strong>\n\nBefore I knew it, with friends, I’d pop out how much a collection of things we’d need for a party would cost. I’d add sales tax (I lived in California then, where they have sales tax—go, Oregon, where we don’t!), and come up with the amount each person would need to contribute.\n\nPeople used to widen their eyes at me and pull out their calculators. I have to admit that my smile got a little smug sometimes.\n\n<strong>Did I somehow get smarter? Heck, no. Ha!</strong>\n\nIn playing the <a href=\"/blog/more-ways-to-play-the-names-for-10-game-to-help-kids-become-math-wizards-and-you-too\">Names for 10 game</a> with kids and showing them how to count coins like in the video below, where Eli counts coins and puts together different combinations to make the same amounts, <strong>I developed and reconfigured neural pathways in my brain.</strong>\n\nAnd so can you!\n\nYour kids can too!\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"958802795733885836\" class=\"wcustomhtml\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" align=\"left\"><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/284257095\" width=\"640\" height=\"352\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\n\n<a href=\"https://vimeo.com/284257095\">Coin Video</a> from <a href=\"https://vimeo.com/user83464375\">Kirdy Molan</a> on <a href=\"https://vimeo.com\">Vimeo</a>.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\">\nOnce these patterns become second nature, you won’t believe how many other math concepts and operations will become easier.\n\nIf you missed the two Names for 10 posts, you can find them <a href=\"/blog/names-for-ten-the-game-that-boosts-kids-math-skills\">here</a> and <a href=\"/blog/more-ways-to-play-the-names-for-10-game-to-help-kids-become-math-wizards-and-you-too\">here</a>.\n\n<strong>How do your kids earn money to toss in a piggy bank and count it later?</strong>\n\nIf you know another helpful math game, please share it with us!\n\nHappy counting!\n\nTrish W.\n\n</div>', 'Help Your Child Become a Math Whiz—And Become One Too!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'help-your-child-become-a-math-whiz-and-become-one-too', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:39:44', '2018-10-10 19:39:44', '', 0, 'https://thebrainstages.com/2018/08/17/help-your-child-become-a-math-whiz-and-become-one-too/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(19, 2, '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Learn More About Brain Stages</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"left\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"alignleft\"><img src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/published/twilkinson-tealblouse.jpg?1518317464\" alt=\"Picture\"/><figcaption>Trish Wilkinson, Author and Licensed Educator<br/></figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\nHi there,\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Do you have a question? Would you like to submit a video with your child that you think would be helpful for other parents and their kids? Would you like me to speak or do a workshop in your community?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whatever is on your mind, I\'d love to hear from you! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Trish Wilkinson<br/>Co-author<br/><em>Brain Stages — </em><em>How to Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It,<br/>K – 5</em><br/>Available August 28, 2018, <a href=\"https://www.sandrajonaspublishing.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Sandra Jonas Publishing</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:wpforms/form-selector {\"formId\":\"137\"} /-->', 'Contact Trish', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'contact-trish-brain-stages', '', '', '2018-10-10 20:53:33', '2018-10-10 20:53:33', '', 0, 'https://thebrainstages.com/contact-trish-brain-stages/', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(20, 2, '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '2018-10-04 23:01:39', '<h2 class=\"wsite-content-title\"><span style=\"color: #515151; font-size: medium;\"><em><strong>How to Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It, K–5</strong></em></span></h2>\n<div>\n<div style=\"height: 20px; overflow: hidden; width: 100%;\">&nbsp;</div>\n</div>\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":33,\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://thebrainstages.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/brainstagescover-exp4-7d-stroke_1_orig.jpg\" alt=\"Brain Stages Cover\" class=\"wp-image-33\"/><figcaption>Brain Stages Cover</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Who says kids don’t come with instructions?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We’re pleased to announce the first edition of <em>Brain Stages</em>, a comprehensive grade-by-grade guide through the elementary school years.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>​Written in a friendly, conversational style, this book gives you useful tools to boost your kids’ brainpower and help them develop social skills, laying the foundation for them to become happy, successful adults.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Backed by research and experience and filled with fun games, insider information, and amazing life hacks for raising kids, <em>Brain Stages</em> invites parents and caregivers to enjoy kids more and stress less while bringing up well-adjusted humans.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<br>\n<br>\n<p style=\"color: #331D6E\"><em><strong>“Finally, a guide to help your child enjoy learning based upon the latest brain research and explained by a veteran teacher, who offers parents fun, practical strategies.”<br>— S. Cradduck, Licensed Educational Psychologist​.</strong></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Brain Stages Book', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'brain-stages-book-brain-stages', '', '', '2018-10-13 22:10:35', '2018-10-13 22:10:35', '', 0, 'https://thebrainstages.com/brain-stages-book-brain-stages/', 0, 'page', '', 0),
