(71, 1, '2018-10-08 12:48:19', '2018-10-08 12:48:19', '<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Learn More About Brain Stages</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/published/twilkinson-tealblouse.jpg?1518317464\" alt=\"Picture\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\nHi there,\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Do you have a question? Would you like to submit a video with your child that you think would be helpful for other parents and their kids? Would you like me to speak or do a workshop in your community?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whatever is on your mind, I\'d love to hear from you! I\'ll respond within 24 hours.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Trish Wilkinson<br/>Co-author<br/><em>Brain Stages — </em><em>How to Raise Smart, Confident Kids and Have Fun Doing It,<br/>K – 5</em><br/>Available August 28, 2018, <a href=\"https://www.sandrajonaspublishing.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Sandra Jonas Publishing</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Contact Trish', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '19-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-10-08 12:48:19', '2018-10-08 12:48:19', '', 19, 'https://thebrainstages.com/2018/10/08/19-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(72, 1, '2018-10-10 19:37:36', '2018-10-10 19:37:36', '<div>\n<div class=\"wsite-image wsite-image-border-none \" style=\"padding-top:0px;padding-bottom:30px;margin-left:0px;margin-right:0px;text-align:center\"> <a> <img src=\"https://thebrainstages.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/eli-red-light-green-light_1_orig.png\" alt=\"Picture\" style=\"width:auto;max-width:100%\"> </a>\n<div style=\"display:block;font-size:90%\"></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;\">Do you have or know a child who writes letters backwards sometimes? The most commonly flipped letters are <strong><em>b</em></strong> and <strong><em>d,</em></strong> but kids have been known to form letters every which way.\n\nWhen I was little, I often confused the b and d until I learned the trick Eli and I are about to show you in the less than 3-minute video. The <strong>Red Light, Green Light</strong> game, given to me by a resource specialist in San Diego, incorporates the trick my second-grade teacher gave me (more decades ago than I\'d like to admit).\n\n<strong>Playing Red Light, Green Light has helped kids of all ages, even children who have learning disabilities, figure out which way the letters are supposed to go — not just the b and d but the whole alphabet. </strong>\n\nWe take writing skills for granted, <a href=\"http://theconversation.com/explainer-how-the-brain-changes-when-we-learn-to-read-76783\">but several kinds of connections between neurons, synapses, and little organs in the brain are involved in processing language</a>. It isn’t a wonder that kids get mixed up sometimes. Holding the pencil with an extra finger on top or some other impractical position can make writing harder (click <a href=\"http://thebrainstages.com/blog/the-best-pencil-grip-the-secret-to-easier-writing\" target=\"_blank\">here</a> to see how to fix pencil grip). Add starting letters in wonky places, or writing letters from the bottom-up instead of the top-down, and writing can become an unpleasant chore.\n\nLuckily, with a bit of fun and practice, neural pathways can access revised information stored in brain’s memory centers.\n\nThe<strong> Red Light, Green Light </strong>game retrains kids how to write letters from <strong>top to bottom</strong> and practices movement from <strong>left to right</strong>, which can improve both reading and writing.\n\nWatch Eli play the game with me in the short video. Initially, when we played the game a few weeks ago, he wrote both <strong><em>b</em></strong> and <em><strong>d</strong></em> from bottom to top. Now that he knows how to form the letters from top to bottom, he told me (and Michelle, his mom, confirmed) that writing has gotten much easier for him. And his reading has improved too!\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"wsite-video\">\n<div title=\"Video: red_light_green_light_game_700.mp4\" class=\"wsite-video-wrapper wsite-video-height-480 wsite-video-align-center\">\n<div id=\"wsite-video-container-884805677828382045\" class=\"wsite-video-container\" style=\"margin: 10px 0 10px 0;\"> 						<iframe allowtransparency=\"true\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" id=\"video-iframe-884805677828382045\" src=\"about:blank\"> 						</iframe> 						<script> 							document.getElementById(\"video-iframe-884805677828382045\").style.opacity = 0; 							document.getElementById(\"wsite-video-container-884805677828382045\").style.background = \"none\"; 							var videoIframe884805677828382045Content = \'<!DOC\'+\'TYPE ht\'+\'ml>\' 								+ \'<he\'+\'ad>\' 								+ \'<scr\'+\'ipt type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/2.1.4/jquery.min.js\">\\x3C/script>\' 								+ \'<scr\'+\'ipt type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"//www.weebly.com/weebly/apps/generateVideo.php?source=weebly&output=js&elementid=884805677828382045&user=114011163&ineditor=0&align=center&margintop=10px&marginbottom=10px&downloadable=1&height=480&video=red_light_green_light_game_700.mp4&image=red_light_green_light_game_700.jpg\">\\x3C/script>\' 								+ \'\'+\'ad>\' 								+ \'<bo\'+\'dy style=\"margin:0; padding: 0;border:none;overflow:hidden;\">\' 								+ \'\'+\'dy>\'+\'ml>\'; 							setTimeout(function() { 								var videoIframe884805677828382045Actual =  document.getElementById(\"video-iframe-884805677828382045\").contentDocument; 								videoIframe884805677828382045Actual.open().write(videoIframe884805677828382045Content); 								videoIframe884805677828382045Actual.close(); 							}, 500); 						</script>\n\n<style> 							#wsite-video-container-884805677828382045{ 								background: url(//www.weebly.com/uploads/red_light_green_light_game_700.jpg); 							}  							#video-iframe-884805677828382045{ 								background: url(//cdn2.editmysite.com/images/util/videojs/play-icon.png?1534365523); 							}  							#wsite-video-container-884805677828382045, #video-iframe-884805677828382045{ 								background-repeat: no-repeat; 								background-position:center; 							}  							@media only screen and (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2), 								only screen and (        min-device-pixel-ratio: 2), 								only screen and (                min-resolution: 192dpi), 								only screen and (                min-resolution: 2dppx) { 									#video-iframe-884805677828382045{ 										background: url(//cdn2.editmysite.com/images/util/videojs/@2x/play-icon.png?1534365523); 										background-repeat: no-repeat; 										background-position:center; 										background-size: 70px 70px; 									} 							} 						</style>\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;\">\n<strong>Here\'s how to play Red Light-Green Light</strong>:\n\n1. You’ll need a red crayon and a green crayon. Why crayons? Because kids can feel the wax, and the tactile sensation helps to solidify the concept. You’ll also need lined paper. Any kind will do, but in most grocery stores now, they sell tablets with a top line, a middle dotted line, or \"belt line\", and a bottom line. When learning, or relearning, how to form letters, that belt line is helpful.\n\n2. Remind your child that green means “GO” and red means “STOP.” Put a green dot where the letter begins and continue with green dots for the entire letter on the first several tries. Place a red dot to signify where the letter should stop. Watch to make sure your child begins and ends the letter in the right places.\n\n</div>\n<span class=\"imgPusher\" style=\"float:left;height:0px\"></span><span style=\"display: table;width:auto;position:relative;float:left;max-width:100%;;clear:left;margin-top:0px;*margin-top:0px\"><a><img src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/editor/img-1869.jpg?1525727356\" style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 30px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 20px; border-width:0; max-width:100%\" alt=\"Brain Stages Writing Hack\" class=\"galleryImageBorder wsite-image\"></a><span style=\"display: table-caption; caption-side: bottom; font-size: 90%; margin-top: -30px; margin-bottom: 30px; text-align: center;\" class=\"wsite-caption\"></span></span>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;display:block;\">\n<em>Note: </em>A lowercase <strong><em>b</em> </strong>starts at the top line, goes down to the bottom line, up to the middle, and around to form the “belly.” After your child gets familiar with how to form the letter, give the direction “Down, up, and around,” and have your child say it with you.</div>\n\n<hr style=\"width:100%;clear:both;visibility:hidden;\">\n\n<span class=\"imgPusher\" style=\"float:left;height:0px\"></span><span style=\"display: table;width:auto;position:relative;float:left;max-width:100%;;clear:left;margin-top:0px;*margin-top:0px\"><a><img src=\"http://thebrainstages.com/uploads/1/1/4/0/114011163/editor/img-1872.jpg?1525727322\" style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 20px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 20px; border-width:0; max-width:100%\" alt=\"Brain Stages Writing Hack\" class=\"galleryImageBorder wsite-image\"></a><span style=\"display: table-caption; caption-side: bottom; font-size: 90%; margin-top: -20px; margin-bottom: 20px; text-align: center;\" class=\"wsite-caption\"></span></span>\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;display:block;\">A lowercase <strong><em>d</em> </strong>is formed like an <em><strong>a</strong></em> with a long stick. Like an <em><strong>a</strong></em> begins just below the middle line, goes up to the middle line, and around to form the “derrier” (French for backside — kids get a kick out of that). The <em><strong>d</strong></em> is formed like an <strong><em>a</em></strong>, except the pencil reaches all the way to the top line and back down to the bottom line. Say with your child, “Around, up, and down.\"</div>\n\n<hr style=\"width:100%;clear:both;visibility:hidden;\">\n\n<div class=\"paragraph\" style=\"text-align:left;\">3. When your child feels comfortable with tracing the letters with lots of green dots, make more letters with fewer and fewer dots until no more are needed. Place only a green dot to mark where the letter begins and a red dot where the letter is to end.\n\n<em>Hint: </em>Get a crayon sharpener (pencil sharpeners work too). Making dots with dull crayons makes them bigger than optimal.\n\nIf your child still reverses a letter using green and red “lights,” help create a tactile memory by writing the entire letter with a green crayon<em>.</em> Then gently guide the pencil in his hand to trace the letter 10 times as consistently as possible.\n\nAnd have fun!\n\nBe liberal with the car engine sounds when you start at the green light and the brake sounds when you stop at the red light.\n\nPlay <strong>Red Light, Green Light </strong>for several days in a row and watch your child\'s writing transform!\n\nThe beauty of educational games is they often have wonderful side effects. <strong>Red Light, Green Light</strong> helps in grasping direction of movement. Truly understanding left to right is a huge help in learning to read.\n\n</div>\n<div>\n<div id=\"736789382366100066\" align=\"left\" style=\"width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;\" class=\"wcustomhtml\">\n<!-- AddToAny BEGIN -->\n<div class=\"a2a_kit a2a_kit_size_32 a2a_default_style\">\n<a class=\"a2a_dd\" href=\"https://www.addtoany.com/share\"></a>\n<a class=\"a2a_button_facebook\"></a>\n<a class=\"a2a_button_twitter\"></a>\n<a class=\"a2a_button_google_plus\"></a>\n<a class=\"a2a_button_linkedin\"></a></div>\n<script async=\"\" src=\"https://static.addtoany.com/menu/page.js\"></script>\n<!-- AddToAny END -->\n\n</div>\n</div>', '“Red Light–Green Light”: Make Kids Better Writers', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '17-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-10-10 19:37:36', '2018-10-10 19:37:36', '', 17, 'https://thebrainstages.com/2018/10/10/17-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
